                <fr:title text="Axiom scheme of replacement">Axiom scheme of replacement</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Axiom</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> be a set, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathtt {P}{\mathopen {}\left (\mathtt {x},\mathtt {y}\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> be a formula in the language of set theory such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\forall  i\in  I\mathpunct {.} \exists ! S\mathpunct {.} \mathtt {P}{\mathopen {}\left (i,S\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> holds. Then the collection of sets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathtt {P}{\mathopen {}\left (i,S\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> holds for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i\in  I]]></fr:tex> holds forms a set.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>This is <fr:em>almost</fr:em> saying that the <fr:link href="jms-00N6.xml" title="Direct image" addr="jms-00N6" type="local">direct image</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> under <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathtt {P}]]></fr:tex> is a set, but this doesn’t actually make sense because we do not have a way to speak about a “relation” between a set and the class of all sets. This strange situation is clarified by other foundational system that go beyond the limitations of the Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory that we have studied in this course.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
